"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"191"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/916/tags","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/916/relationships/tags"}},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"60"},{"type":"contributions","id":"61"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40659"}],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/916/contributions","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/916/relationships/contributions"}}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"123959","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/123959"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for review of his type 2 diabetes management. He has a four-year history of diabetes with recent poor glycaemic control. He has a medical history of hypertension and hyperlipidaemia. His current medications include metformin, simvastatin, and perindopril. He does not smoke and works as an office manager.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His BMI is 32 kg/m\u00b2. Recent investigations reveal an HbA1c of 10.0% (3.0-6.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in managing his diabetes and obesity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intensive medical management with lifestyle modification","Laparoscopic gastric banding","Duodeno-jejunal exclusion tube","Vertical banded gastroplasty","Roux-en-Y gastric bypass"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has a BMI of 32 kg/m\u00b2 (class I obesity) with poorly controlled type 2 diabetes (HbA1c 10.0%). According to current guidelines, bariatric surgery is indicated for BMI \u226535 kg/m\u00b2 or BMI \u0026gt;30-with obesity-related comorbidities when glycaemic targets have not been achieved despite optimal lifestyle modification and medical treatment. This patient does not meet these criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntensive medical management with lifestyle modification\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate approach for this patient. This includes optimising his diabetes medications (potentially adding additional agents to metformin), implementing structured dietary counselling, increasing physical activity, and addressing behavioural factors. The significantly elevated HbA1c indicates urgent need for medical optimisation before any surgical consideration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopic gastric banding\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the patient\u0027s BMI does not meet surgical criteria. Additionally, this procedure has fallen out of favour due to high complication rates and poor long-term outcomes compared to other bariatric procedures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDuodeno-jejunal exclusion tube\u003C/strong\u003E is an experimental endoscopic procedure not routinely available in Australia and would not be appropriate for a patient who doesn\u0027t meet standard bariatric surgery criteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVertical banded gastroplasty\u003C/strong\u003E is a largely obsolete bariatric procedure that is no longer performed due to poor long-term results and high complication rates. It would not be indicated in this patient regardless.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERoux-en-Y gastric bypass\u003C/strong\u003E is an effective bariatric procedure but is not indicated in this patient as his BMI is below the threshold for surgical intervention. This procedure would only be considered if his BMI increased to \u226535 kg/m\u00b2 and glycaemic targets remained unachieved despite optimal medical management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bariatric surgery is indicated for patients with BMI \u226540 kg/m\u00b2 or BMI 35-39.9 kg/m\u00b2 with obesity-related comorbidities when glycaemic targets are not achieved despite optimal medical treatment.","Intensive medical management with lifestyle modification is the appropriate first-line approach for patients who do not meet bariatric surgery criteria.","Poor glycaemic control (HbA1c 10%) in obesity requires optimisation of medical therapy before considering surgical interventions."],"references":["Ching Lee, P \u0026 Dixon, J 2017, \u0027Bariatric\u2013metabolic surgery: A guide for the primary care physician\u0027, Australian Family Physician, vol. 46, 7/01, pp. 465-471.","Markovic TP, Proietto J, Dixon JB, et al. The Australian Obesity Management Algorithm: A simple tool to guide the management of obesity in primary care. Obes Res Clin Pract. 2022 Sep-Oct;16(5):353-363. Available from: https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S1871-403X(22)00070-9","Shilton H. Bariatric surgery. Aust J Gen Pract. 2025; 54:202-206"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"105345"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/123959/itemRevision","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/123959/relationships/itemRevision"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"916"},"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/123959/question","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/123959/relationships/question"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/123959/stemMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/123959/relationships/stemMedia"}},"explanationMedia":{"data":[],"links":{"related":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/123959/explanationMedia","self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/123959/relationships/explanationMedia"}}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"105345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/105345"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-11-02T10:05:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-11-02T10:05:15